  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>How to Build Muscle While Losing Fat</h2>
    <p>Body recomposition — simultaneous fat loss and muscle gain — is most achievable for:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Complete beginners to resistance training (high responsiveness to training stimulus)</li>
      <li>People returning after a training break (muscle memory speeds regain)</li>
      <li>People with significant excess fat (larger energy surplus available from stored fat)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The key requirements: adequate protein (2.0–2.4g/kg bodyweight), consistent resistance training (2–3x/week), and a modest calorie deficit or maintenance (not an aggressive deficit, which prioritises fat loss over muscle gain).</p>
    <div class="warn-callout"><p>⚠️ Don't let scale stagnation discourage you during a combined fat loss and muscle gain phase. Take monthly progress photos and waist measurements — these will show changes the scale misses.</p></div>
  </div>


  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Practical Guide: Losing Fat While Building (or Keeping) Muscle</h2>
    <p>The goal of most people isn't just to lose weight — it's to improve body composition: less fat, more muscle. This is sometimes called a "body recomposition." Here's how to do it effectively:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Eat a moderate calorie deficit (300–400 kcal/day):</strong> Large deficits accelerate muscle loss. Smaller deficits allow fat loss while preserving muscle, especially combined with resistance training.</li>
      <li><strong>Prioritise protein (1.6–2.2 g/kg body weight):</strong> Protein provides amino acids for muscle protein synthesis and is the most satiating macronutrient, reducing hunger on a deficit.</li>
      <li><strong>Train with progressive overload (2–4 sessions/week):</strong> Resistance training sends a signal to preserve muscle tissue even when calories are restricted. Without this signal, the body has no reason to keep metabolically expensive muscle.</li>
      <li><strong>Sleep 7–9 hours:</strong> Growth hormone — which drives muscle repair and fat metabolism — is primarily released during deep sleep. Sleep deprivation disrupts both processes simultaneously.</li>
      <li><strong>Be patient:</strong> Body recomposition is slower than pure fat loss. A realistic rate is 0.5–1% body fat reduction per month while maintaining or slightly increasing muscle mass. Progress shows in the mirror and measurements before it shows on the scale.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="callout"><p>💡 Track progress with waist circumference + body weight together. Losing 1 cm off your waist while weight stays the same = muscle gain + fat loss happening simultaneously.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>How Long Does It Take to Build Visible Muscle?</h2>
    <p>Beginners ("newbie gains"): 1–2 kg of muscle in the first 2–3 months with consistent training and adequate protein. After the first year, gains slow to approximately 0.5–1 kg per month for men and 0.25–0.5 kg per month for women.</p>
    <p>Key factors determining muscle-building speed: training consistency, sleep quality, protein intake, training programme (progressive overload), genetics, and age. Testosterone levels in men generally support faster muscle gain — which is why men typically see faster recomposition results than women at the same effort level.</p>
    <p>Important: muscle takes up significantly less volume than the same weight of fat. 1 kg of muscle is roughly 15–20% smaller in size than 1 kg of fat. This is why people often look visibly leaner and more toned even before the scale moves much.</p>
  </div>

